AB  - Toxin-antidote (TA) elements are selfish DNA sequences that bias their
      transmission to the next generation. TAs typically consist of two linked
      genes: a toxin and an antidote. The toxin kills progeny that do not
      inherit the TA, while the antidote counteracts the toxin in progeny that
      inherit the TA. Many TAs have been found in bacteria and archaea, but only
      a few in eukaryotes. We previously discovered two TAs in C. elegans:
      peel-1/zeel-1 and sup-35/pha-1. Here, we report a third TA in C. elegans
      which has several distinctive features. Unlike the toxins PEEL-1 and
      SUP-35, the new maternally deposited toxin causes larval arrest rather
      than embryonic lethality, raising the question of how the toxicity is
      delayed to this stage. We identified the toxin and antidote genes, which
      encode proteins of unknown function. We detected toxin mRNA transcripts in
      Z2/Z3 cells in larvae, which suggests that the transcript is sequestered
      from translation and degradation in germ cells. At the population level,
      previously described TAs are characterized by presence or absence of both
      the toxin and the antidote in a given individual. In contrast, we
      identified three clades with distinct haplotypes at the new TA locus. In
      addition to strains with an intact TA and a second set of strains that
      lost the toxin, many strains, including the standard laboratory strain N2,
      carry an intact but highly divergent version of the toxin that appears to
      be active. The antidote is pseudogenized in these strains, presenting the
      puzzle of how they inactivate the toxin. Current evidence suggests that
      this is accomplished by MUT-16- and PRG-1-dependent production of small
      interfering RNAs that target the toxin gene. ### Competing Interest
      Statement The authors have declared no competing interest.
